intro: Willughbeia multilocularis, commonly known as the giant willughbeia, is a tropical plant native to the rainforests of northern Queensland, Australia. It is a member of the Araliaceae family and is characterized by its large, palm-like leaves and showy yellow flowers. The plant typically grows as an understory species, thriving in humid, shaded environments with rich, well-drained soil. Its unique morphology includes a stout, woody stem and compound leaves that can reach lengths of up to 2 meters. Willughbeia multilocularis is also noted for its ability to produce a milky sap, which contains various bioactive compounds of interest in scientific research.
